.TH "TEMPORAL.INSTANT.VALUEOF" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Instant.valueOf \- Temporal.Instant.prototype.valueOf()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]valueOf()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R]
instances throws a \f[CR]TypeError\f[R], which prevents
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] instances from being implicitly converted to
primitives when used in arithmetic or comparison operations.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
valueOf()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
None.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Always thrown.
.SH DESCRIPTION
Because both primitive conversion and number conversion call
\f[CR]valueOf()\f[R] before \f[CR]toString()\f[R], if
\f[CR]valueOf()\f[R] is absent, then an expression like
\f[CR]instant1 > instant2\f[R] would implicitly compare them as strings,
which may have unexpected results.
By throwing a \f[CR]TypeError\f[R], \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R]
instances prevent such implicit conversions.
You need to explicitly convert them to numbers using
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant.prototype.epochNanoseconds\f[R], or use the
\f[CR]Temporal.Instant.compare()\f[R] static method to compare them.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Arithmetic and comparison operations on Temporal.Instant
All arithmetic and comparison operations on \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R]
instances should use the dedicated methods or convert them to primitives
explicitly.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] instant1 = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(0);
\f[B]const\f[R] instant2 = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(1000);
instant1 > instant2; \f[I]// TypeError: can\(aqt convert Instant to primitive type\f[R]
instant1.epochNanoseconds > instant2.epochNanoseconds; \f[I]// false\f[R]
Temporal.Instant.compare(instant1, instant2); \f[I]// \-1\f[R]

instant2 \- instant1; \f[I]// TypeError: can\(aqt convert Instant to primitive type\f[R]
instant2.since(instant1).toString(); \f[I]// \(dqPT1S\(dq\f[R]
.EE
